          <h2 class="details-title">Elephanta Caves: A UNESCO World Heritage Site in Mumbai</h2>
          <p>
            Nestled on the serene Elephanta Island, about 11 kilometers off the coast of Mumbai, the Elephanta Caves are
            an exquisite blend of history, art, and spirituality. These rock-cut caves, designated as a UNESCO World
            Heritage Site, date back to the 5th–7th centuries and are a stunning example of ancient Indian rock
            architecture dedicated primarily to Lord Shiva.</p>
          <h5>History and Origin</h5>
          <p>The origins of the Elephanta Caves are steeped in mystery, with historians attributing their creation to
            various dynasties, including the Kalachuri, Rashtrakuta, and Chalukya rulers. Originally known as Gharapuri,
            meaning "the city of caves," the island later came to be called Elephanta after Portuguese explorers
            discovered a massive stone elephant near the island's shore. This stone elephant is now preserved at
            Mumbai's Jijamata Udyan (Rani Baug).</p>
          <h5>Architectural Brilliance</h5>
          <p>The Elephanta Caves consist of two groups:</p>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Hindu Caves</strong>: Five caves dedicated to Lord Shiva.</li>
            <li><strong>Buddhist Caves</strong>: Two smaller caves believed to be Buddhist stupas.</li>
          </ol>
          <h5>Key Highlights of the Caves</h5>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <h5>Trimurti</h5>
              <p>The centerpiece of the caves, this massive 20-foot sculpture depicts the three faces of Lord Shiva:</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d9/Elephanta_Caves_Trimurti.jpg" alt="">
              <ul>
                <li>Creator (Vamadeva)</li>
                <li>Protector (Mahadeva)</li>
                <li>Destroyer (Bhairava)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>
              <h5>Shiva as Nataraja</h5>
              <p>This sculpture portrays Shiva performing the Tandava dance, representing the cycle of creation and
                destruction.</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://elephanta.co.in/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Nataraja-at-Elephanta-Caves.jpg" alt="">
            </li>
            <li>
              <h5>Shiva and Parvati on Mount Kailash</h5>
              <p>A serene depiction of Lord Shiva and Goddess Parvati in their heavenly abode, showcasing divine
                harmony.</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://indiainstyle.in/article/A90A9980_IN_Mumbai_Elephanta_Caves_Shiva_Parvati_Kailash_1000.jpg">

            </li>
            <li>
              <h5>Yogeshwara Shiva</h5>
              <p>A representation of Lord Shiva as a yogi, meditating in deep tranquility.</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://elephanta.co.in/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Mahayogi-Shiva-of-Elephanta.jpg" alt="">

            </li>
            <li>
              <h5>Andhakasuravadha</h5>
              <p>This panel illustrates Shiva slaying the demon Andhaka, symbolizing the victory of good over evil.</p>
              <img style="max-width: 100%; max-height: 400px;" src="https://elephanta.co.in/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Andhakasura-Panel-of-Elephanta.jpg" alt="">

            </li>
            <li>
              <h5>Other Panels</h5>
              <p>Depictions of events like the marriage of Shiva and Parvati and the story of Ganga’s descent add to the
                richness of the art.</p>
              </li>
          </ol>
          <h5>Things to Do Around the Caves</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Explore the lush greenery of Elephanta Island.</li>
            <li>Shop for handicrafts and souvenirs at local stalls near the caves.</li>
            <li>Enjoy a peaceful boat ride back to Mumbai at sunset.</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Travel Tips</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Wear comfortable footwear as the caves require climbing several steps.</li>
            <li>Carry water and light snacks, especially if traveling with children.</li>
            <li>Hire a guide or use an audio guide to understand the rich history and significance of the sculptures.
            </li>
